⚫It was concentrated in what is today Greece and along the western coast of Turkey.
⚫However, ancient Greek colonists established cities all around the Mediterranean and along the coast of the Black Sea.
⚫Ancient Greek civilization flourished from the period following Mycenaean civilization, which ended about 1200 BCE, to the death of Alexander the Great, in 323 BCE.
⚫By that time, Greek cultural influence had spread around the Mediterranean and, through Alexander the Great’s campaign of conquest, as far afield as India.
⚫The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.

⚫It is a historical and archaeological city in southern Jordan.
⚫By the 2nd century BC Petra was the capital city of Nabataeans kingdom.
⚫Petra is famous for its rock-cut architecture and water conduit system.
⚫The Treasury (Al Khazneh) is the most known building in the city.
⚫In 2007, Al-Khazneh was voted one of the New 7 Wonders of the World.
⚫Petra is also called the 'Rose City' because of the colour of the stone from which it is carved.
⚫It has been a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1985.
⚫UNESCO has described Petra as "one of the most precious cultural properties of man's cultural heritage".
⚫Visitor numbers reached 1.1 million in 2019.

(Cattedrale di Santa Maria del Fiore )
⚫Located their in Florence, Italy.
⚫The basilica is one of Italy's largest churches, and its dome is the largest brick dome ever constructed.
⚫The construction begun in 1296 in the Gothic style to a design of Arnolfo di Cambio.
⚫But by the beginning of the 15th century, after a hundred years of construction, the structure was still missing its dome.
⚫In 1436, Filippo Brunelleschi completed the structure by building the dome.

🔘The Karnak Temple Complex 🔘
⚫The Karnak Temple Complex, commonly known as Karnak (from Arabic Khurnak meaning "fortified village").

⚫It comprises a vast mix of decayed temples, chapels, pylons, and other buildings near Luxor, in Egypt.

⚫Built, added to, dismantled, restored, enlarged and decorated over nearly 1500 years.

⚫Construction at the complex began during the reign of Senusret I in the Middle Kingdom (around 2000–1700 BC) and continued into the Ptolemaic period (305–30 BC).

🔘large Mosaic discovered beneath a Hotel🔘
⚫In 2009, a construction crew digging the foundation for a new hotel in Antakya, Turkey, uncovered a vast mosaic dating back to the Roman and Hellenic times, more than 2000 years ago, along with more than 35,000 artifacts (glassware, coins and jewellery).

⚫Archaeologists at the site believe the geometric work once decorated the floor of a public building, it's 1,050m² (9,000 square-foot).

⚫The main panel is bordered by a beautiful collection of animal ‘paintings’ in mosaic.
⚫Pairs of dogs, goats, deer, hares, and birds face each other over food on eight landscape-shaped panels, while birds flutter in the corner squares.

⚫Although vast segments of the original mosaic are still intact, others have rippled and disappeared due to a series of earthquakes in 526 and 528 A.D.

⚫The Asfuroğlu group who own the hotel decided to embrace the challenge, integrating the archaeological find into the hotel’s blueprints.
⚫11 years later, the 200-room Museum Hotel Antakya opened its doors.

🔘Moray🔘
⚫Is an archaeological site in Peru.
⚫The site contains unusual Inca ruins, mostly consisting of several terraced circul depressions, the largest of which is approximately 30 m (98 ft) deep.

⚫The ringed Incan ruins known as Moray have long been a mystery, but it is looking more and more likely that the nested stone rings may have been part of a large-scale agricultural experiment.

⚫Studies have shown that many of the terraces contain soil that must have been imported from other parts of the region.
⚫The temperature at the top of the pits varies from that at the bottom by as much as 15ºC, creating a series of micro-climates that match many of the varied conditions across the Incan empire.
⚫leading to the conclusion that the rings were used as a test bed to see what crops could grow where.

🔘Zellaer Castle🔘
⚫locally known as Kasteel van Zellaer.
⚫Located north of the village of Bonheiden, Belgium.
⚫The first castle at this site was probably built during the 13th century by Wouter VI Berthout, Lord of Mechelen.
⚫In the 17th century the medieval castle was substantially rebuilt.
⚫In 1886 the castle passed on to baron Gustave de Vrière's family.
⚫Gustave then had the old castle demolished and had the present castle built upon its foundations by the architect Heugenbaarts from Mechelen, between 1888 and 1892.

🔘Abu Simbel temples🔘
⚫Abu Simbel is two massive rock-cut temples in the village of Abu Simbel, Aswan, Egypt.
⚫The twin temples were originally carved out of the mountainside and took about twenty years to be complete.
⚫The two temples were built by the Egyptian king Ramses II (reigned 1279–13 BCE).
⚫In the mid-20th century, when the reservoir that was created by the construction of the nearby Aswan High Dam threatened to submerge Abu Simbel, a huge project started to save both of the temples.
⚫They were completely disassembled and reconstructed on a high ground more than 200 feet (60 metres) above their previous site. In all, some 16,000 blocks were moved.

🔘The Pyramid of Cestius🔘
⚫It is an ancient pyramid located in Rome, Italy.
⚫Due to its incorporation into the city's fortifications, it is today one of the best-preserved ancient buildings in Rome.

⚫The pyramid was built about 18–12 BC as a tomb for Gaius Cestius a member of the Epulones religious corporation.
⚫The Epulones arranged feasts and public banquets at festivals and games.
⚫They constituted one of the four great religious corporations of ancient Roman priests.
⚫The tomb was completed in 330 days and was one of two pyramid shaped tombs in the city of Rome.

⚫The pyramid measures 100 Roman feet (29.6 m) square at the base and stands 125 Roman feet (37 m) high.
⚫Inside the pyramid there is the burial chamber, measuring 5.95 metres long, 4.10 m wide and 4.80 m high.
⚫Two marble bases were found next to the pyramid during excavations in the 1660s, complete with fragments of the bronze statues that originally had stood on their tops.

🔘The Bridge of Girsu🔘
⚫Located in Girsu (Modern day Tello), Iraq.
⚫The Sumerian city of Girsu is one of the earliest known cities in the world.
⚫The city is estimated to be nearly 5,000 years old.
⚫The 4000 years old bridge in Girsu is the oldest bridge ever discovered in the world.

🌉The baked brick bridge when it was first discovered, was variously interpreted as a temple, dam and water regulator.
⚫Only recently that the structure was identified as a bridge over an ancient waterway.
⚫It was at Girsu that evidence of the Sumerian civilization was first discovered in the form of thousands of cuneiform tablets with records of economic, administrative and commercial matters of the city.

⚫Treasure hunters then looted large quantities of tablets and other artefacts and sold them to collectors.
⚫It is estimated that between 35,000 to 40,000 tablets were looted from Girsu.

🔘The Baths of the Seven Wise Men🔘
⚫A well-preserved Roman bathhouse from the 2nd century, Located in Ostia, southwest of Rome, Italy.
⚫The thermal baths were built under "Hadrian" and are located between two blocks of houses.
⚫The centre of the complex is a round hall that once had a dome, its floor shows a black and white mosaic depicts hunting.

⚫From here, arches led to the bathrooms :
A warm bath ( caldarium ), equipped with a mosaic with the representation of seahorses.
⚫A cold bathroom (frigidarium), with a wall painting of a bathing Venus.
⚫The bathhouse was once richly decorated with sculptures.

⚫In the apodyterium (changing room) there are pictures of the seven wise men.
7️⃣The Seven Sages of Greece or Seven Wise Men was the title given by classical Greek tradition to seven philosophers, statesmen, and law-givers of the 6th century BC who were renowned for their wisdom.

🔘The temples of Mount Fanjing🔘
⚫Located in Tongren, Guizhou province, is the highest peak of the Wuling Mountains in southwestern China.
⚫Fanjing is the highest peak of the Wuling Mountains, stretching 8,430 feet above sea level.
⚫To reach the temples you have to walk up more than 8,000 steps or take a cable car ride up.

⚫Mount Fanjing is considered a sacred mountain of Chinese Buddhism.
⚫Buddhism first came to the region in 639 during the Tang Dynasty, and the temples were likely constructed sometime after that.

⚫The temples were partially destroyed in the late 1500s during the Bozhou Rebellion, but they have been restored.
⚫It was named a UNESCO World Heritage Site in July 2018.
